  "8": {
    "John H. Walton, John K. Riches": "My lord the king! With this form of address David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\nacknowledges Saul\u2019s position and his own submission to the king\u2019s\nauthority.3 Yet the last time someone addressed Saul with the\nwords \u201cmy lord,\u201d that person ended up dead despite making a\npowerful case for his innocence (see 22:12), so at this point there is\ntension in the plot.\nv. 8), \u201cking of Israel\u201d once (",
    "Commentary Vol. 2": "David `[char_David_Rut_4]` also arose afterward, etc.] After Saul was gone:\nand went out of the cave; where he had been all the time that Saul had been\nin it:\nand cried after Saul: with a loud voice: my lord the king; by which titles\nSaul would know that he was called unto:\nand when Saul looked behind him; to see who it was that called unto him:\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]` stooped with his face to the earth, and bowed himself: giving\n[v_1Sa_20_41] reverence and honour to him as a king; (see Gill on \u201c<092041>1 Samuel 20:41\u201d).\nVer."
  },
  "10": {
    "John H. Walton, John K. Riches": "the Lord delivered you into my hands\ufffd There is irony here\nwhen one contrasts David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s words with the narrator\u2019s statement in\n23:14, \u201cGod did not give David `[char_David_Rut_4]` into his hands.\u201d\nI will not lay my hand\ufffd The Hebrew expression \u201clay/raise a hand\u201d\n[v_1Sa_22_17] was last used in the story in 1 Samuel 22:17, which says that Saul\u2019s\nservants refused to \u201craise a hand\u201d (shalah yad) against the Lord\u2019s\npriests. Their restraint, like David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s, stands in stark contrast to\nSaul\u2019s murderous aggression against the priests and against David `[char_David_Rut_4]`.",
    "Commentary Vol. 2": "Behold, this day thine eyes have seen, etc.] Or may see; there is\nfull proof and evidence of it, and which will be presently shown:\n353\nhow that the Lord had delivered thee today into mine hand in the cave;\nfrom whence they were both just come:\nand [some] bade [me] kill thee; some of the men that were with David `[char_David_Rut_4]`,\nsome of his officers or principal friends put him upon it, having a fair\nopportunity, and thinking it no evil, since he was his enemy, and sought his\nlife; or \u201cit said, kill thee\u201d; my heart prompted me to it, that said so at first,\nas Ben Gersom interprets it; some refer it to God, who in his providence\nsaid so, or so it might be understood by David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, as if Providence directed\nhim to it, by giving film such an opportunity of doing it:\nbut [mine eye] spared thee; had pity on him, and notwithstanding the\nsuggestions of friends, and of his own heart at first, or the seeming\ndirection of Providence, yet he had mercy on him, and forbore slaying him:\nand I said, I will not put forth my hand against my lord; and king, whose\nsubject I am:\nfor he [is] the Lord\u2019s anointed; the Lord has raised him to this dignity;\ninvested him with the office of a king, and as such I regard him, and\ntherefore have refrained mine hand from him, from hurting him,\nVer."
  },
  "11": {
    "John H. Walton, John K. Riches": "my father\ufffd David `[char_David_Rut_4]` goes out of his way to express Saul\u2019s\nauthority over him. He addresses him as \u201cmy lord/master\u201d three\ntimes (vv. 6, 8, 10), \u201cking\u201d once (\nv. 11).\nAnd he wept aloud\ufffd This expression elsewhere describes a response\n[v_Gen_21_16] of extreme sorrow (Gen. 21:16; 27:38; Judg. 2:4; 21:2; Ruth 1:9, 14;\n[v_1Sa_11_4] 1 Sam. 11:4; 2 Sam. 3:32; 13:36; Job\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s encounter with Saul occurs somewhere in the region of En\nGedi, where he has been hiding. En Gedi is a large oasis, with the Dead Sea to the\neast and Judean\nwilderness to the west. Its abundant caves, rugged landscape, and water supply\n(pictured here) made it an ideal hideout.\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]` and Saul\u2019s Sons 2:12).4 On at least one occasion feelings of\n[v_Jdg_2_4] guilt appear to be present (Judg. 2:4), but by itself the expression\nneed not imply this. Usually there is a sense of loss or regret that\nprompts this emotional response.",
    "Commentary Vol. 2": "15); which so affected Saul, that he confessed he was more\nrighteous than he, and owned that the kingdom would be his, and only\ndesired him to swear to him not to cut off his offspring, which David `[char_David_Rut_4]` did,\n[v_1Sa_24_16] [v_1Sa_24_17] [v_1Sa_24_18] [v_1Sa_24_19] [v_1Sa_24_20] [v_1Sa_24_21] [v_1Sa_24_22] and so they parted, (<092416>1 Samuel 24:16-22).\nVer.\n11. Moreover, my father, etc.] So he was in a natural sense, as having\nmarried his daughter; and in a civil sense, as he was a king, and was, or\nought to have been, the father of his country, and to treat his subjects as his\nchildren, and David `[char_David_Rut_4]` among the rest:\nsee, yea see, the skirt of thy robe in my hand; look on it again and again;\nview it with the eyes of thy body intently, that thou mayest be satisfied of\nit, and behold with the eyes of thy mind and understanding, and consider\nthat I could as easily have had thine head in my hand as the skirt of thy\nrobe; and here see an instance and proof of the integrity and sincerity of my\nheart, and cordial affections to thee, and an evidence against all the charges\nand accusations of my enemies, and that I have no ill design upon thy\nperson and life, and am far from seeking thy hurt, as they say:\nfor in that I cut off the skirt of thy robe, and killed thee not; not only did\nthat to show that he was in his power, but did not cut off his head, as he\ncould:\n354\nknow thou, and see, that [there is] neither evil nor transgression in mine\nhand; this might be a full conviction to him that he had no ill, neither in his\nheart nor hand, to do unto him:\nand I have not sinned against thee; done nothing to offend him, never\nacted against his will, nor disobeyed any of his commands, or had been\nguilty of one overt act of treason or rebellion, but all the reverse:\nyet thou huntest my soul to take it; pursued him from place to place,\nhunted him in the wildernesses of Ziph and Maon, and upon the rocks of\n[v_1Sa_26_20] Engedi, as a partridge on the mountains, (<092620>1 Samuel 26:20); and lay in\nwait for him to kill him, as the Targum: he may be thought to have penned\nthe \u201cseventh\u201d psalm at this time, or on this occasion; at least there are\nsome passages in it, which seem to refer to his present circumstances,\n[v_Psa_7_1] [v_Psa_7_2] [v_Psa_7_3] [v_Psa_7_4] [v_Psa_7_5] [v_Psa_7_6] [v_Psa_7_7] [v_Psa_7_8] [v_Psa_7_9] [v_Psa_7_10] [v_Psa_7_11] [v_Psa_7_12] [v_Psa_7_13] [v_Psa_7_14] [v_Psa_7_15] [v_Psa_7_16] [v_Psa_7_17] (<190701>"
  },
